Diabetic macular edema (DME) is a complication of diabetes that affects the eyes. It is a condition characterized by the accumulation of fluid in the macula, which is the central part of the retina responsible for sharp, central vision. DME occurs when the blood vessels in the retina, which are damaged by diabetes, leak fluid into the macula, causing it to swell

In people with diabetes, high blood sugar levels can damage the blood vessels in the retina, a condition known as diabetic retinopathy. When the blood vessels are damaged, they can leak fluid and blood into the retina, including the macula, leading to macular edema.

DME can cause vision problems, including blurry or distorted vision, difficulty reading, and an inability to see colors properly. It may affect one or both eyes. If left untreated, DME can progress and cause significant vision loss.

The risk of developing DME is higher in individuals with long-standing diabetes, poorly controlled blood sugar levels, high blood pressure, and high cholesterol. Regular eye examinations are crucial for people with diabetes to detect and manage DME and other diabetic eye complications.

Treatment options for DME include:

Anti-vascular endothelial growth factor (anti-VEGF) injections: These medications are injected into the eye to reduce swelling and leakage by targeting the abnormal blood vessels.

Laser photocoagulation: This treatment uses a laser to seal leaking blood vessels and reduce the swelling in the macula.

Corticosteroids: Steroid medications can be delivered into the eye in the form of injections or implants to reduce inflammation and swelling.

Vitrectomy: In severe cases, when other treatments are not effective, a surgical procedure called vitrectomy may be performed to remove the vitreous gel and any scar tissue that may be causing DME.

It's important for individuals with diabetes to control their blood sugar levels, manage blood pressure and cholesterol, and have regular eye check-ups to detect and manage DME at an early stage.
